<Layout title="ToC Ch.5 — Pushdown Automata" favicon="🔀">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/theory-of-computation/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to Theory of Computation</a>

    <h1>Pushdown Automata</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Maheshwari &amp; Smid &middot; Ch. 5 &middot; <a href="https://cglab.ca/~michiel/TheoryOfComputation/">Introduction to Theory of Computation</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>pushdown automaton</strong> (PDA) is a finite automaton equipped with a stack. The stack gives it memory to count, match, and nest. PDAs recognize exactly the context-free languages.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- PDA definition -->
    <h3>Definition</h3>
    <p>A PDA is a 6-tuple (Q, &Sigma;, &Gamma;, &delta;, q<sub>0</sub>, F):</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>&Gamma;</strong> &mdash; the stack alphabet</li>
      <li><strong>&delta;</strong> &mdash; transition function: Q &times; (&Sigma; &cup; &#123;&epsilon;&#125;) &times; (&Gamma; &cup; &#123;&epsilon;&#125;) &rarr; P(Q &times; (&Gamma; &cup; &#123;&epsilon;&#125;))</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Each transition reads an input symbol (or &epsilon;), pops from the stack (or not), moves to a new state, and pushes to the stack (or not).</p>

    <!-- SVG: PDA with stack -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 440 200" class="w-full max-w-lg" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
